## Why this fits

- It's **concrete and falsifiable** in a way "saturation 1–5" isn't. You can defend or attack a number; you can't really attack a 3/5 vibes-rating.
- It uses data the user can actually pull (TikTok search, Roblox charts) — both already mentioned elsewhere in the docs.
- It nudges the user toward research before commitment, which is the whole point of the brainstorm phase.
- It doesn't replace the existing saturation check — it's the more rigorous version of it. The 1–5 score still has its place for fast comparative scoring across 7 concepts; the ratio is for the final shortlist of 2.

